metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #191
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: Diyalebuka #64
metadata.description:
Diyalebuka - "Thank you"! 

With this piece I hope to express my thanks and joy for being alive and able to create art. I hope the patterns and textures will bring you joy.

This piece is inspired by the patterns of the Ndebele of Southern Africa and the First Nations Salish of Vancouver Island.

* There are over 100 palettes arranged into 6 distinct families
* There can be between 2 and 10 bars

(The artwork will fit your available window and may take a while to generate if it's a larger resolution)

metadata.name: Lorda #56
metadata.description:
------------
Introduction
------------
Argentina is world-renowned for its exquisite wine, and the Malbec grape has long been a celebrated variety. While most of the country’s wine comes from the region of Cuyo, specifically the province of Mendoza, there is another hidden gem that is often overlooked: Entre Rios.

Named after the two massive rivers that surround it, Entre Rios is a province located in the northeast of Argentina. What many people don’t know is that it boasts a long and fascinating history of wine production that dates back to the early 19th century.

During a recent visit to Entre Rios, I had the pleasure of exploring a small vineyard located near the Parana river. As I walked among the vines, I couldn’t help but feel inspired by their vibrant colors, intricate patterns of the leaves, and the beautiful clusters of grapes. It was clear to me that there was something truly special about the vineyards of Entre Rios.

As I delved deeper into the region’s history, I discovered that until 1937, Entre Rios was one of the largest wine producers in the country, with over 60 vineyards operating in the province. However, a national law was passed that year creating the Regulating Board of Wine, which concentrated and granted exclusivity to wine production in Cuyo. It wasn’t until 1993 that the law was repealed, allowing vineyards to be planted and modified throughout the country.

Today, Entre Rios is home to a small but thriving wine industry that is known for its unique blends and varietals. One of the most notable grapes is the Tannat, which was once the predominant variety in the region.

Inspired by the beauty of these vineyards, I decided to create a generative art collection that celebrates the colors, shapes, and textures of the grapes and vines called ‘Lorda’.


-----------
About Lorda
-----------
Tannat originates in southwest France (Madiran). However, it was not very admired there, so Tannat began its journey: it moved to our country, in the trunks of a Basque, Juan Jauregui, and settled in Entre Rios towards the end of the 1800s. This farmer nicknamed “El Lorda” planted Tannat in Concordia and managed to make a quite respectable wine. The grape took that nickname and became known as Lorda.


-----

Press "e" to save a high res png while in live mode.

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2023)

Made with P5js and <3

metadata.name: The Distant peaks #89
metadata.description:
The Distant Peaks is the first generative art release that combines my collection on Objkt:
"The Windless Summit and The Distant sea"

Since the beginning, I want to create a plotter printer or generative art style. but I don't have the basic knowledge to do creative coding, so I tried to replicate it with The Help of artificial intelligence and now I'm collaborating with @rosetta196 to help me experiment with the generative art area.

Each piece in this collection is a unique and intricate representation of the rugged peaks and sweeping vistas of mountains, as well as the calming of the ocean's waves. The colors, textures, and movements of the artwork are all meticulously crafted through code, with every detail carefully considered to capture the essence of these natural wonders.

The use of pure code to generate these landscapes serves to highlight the beauty and complexity of mathematics and computer programming. 
It is a testament to the power of technology and its ability to create stunning works of art that evoke deep emotions and inspire creativity.

As you gaze upon the art, you are drawn into a world of tranquility and natural beauty. The peacefulness of the mountains and the endless expanse of the ocean come to life, inviting you to explore and discover the wonders of the natural world. 
This art project is a celebration of the beauty of nature and the incredible potential of generative art.


by Samanta and Rosetta196 2023

metadata.name: Transition: Multidimensional #54
metadata.description:
The world is always and has always been in constant transition. Transitions have created and destroyed everything. Understanding and living with transitions is fundamental to being in the universe.

Transition is not one-dimensional. It is not just a move from A to B, but rather a constant shifting between A to F to % to 9 to AA to €. It is multi-faceted and multi-dimensional. This implies that binaries are merely imagined.

With this piece, I explore the idea of transitions being multidimensional by using shapes which progressively increase in edge count in all manner of ways. 

You’ll witness transitions that happen slowly, quickly, in fits and starts, and chaotically.

You’ll find transitions placed in circles, grids, towers, spirals, and more.

You’ll see transitions in multiple color schemes including inverted versions of each scheme. 

Interactions

A - Start/stop cumulative animation

B - Start/stop independent animation

S - Save image

metadata.name: KAKOFONI ORQUESTRA #79
metadata.description:
Check the fxhash article to read about the creative process behind it.

Click on the screen to start the music.

Keyboard commands:
1 - turn on/off the track 1
2 - turn on/off the track 1 reverb
3 - turn on/off the track 2
4 - turn on/off the track 2 reverb

I strongly recommend reloading the piece after 15 minutes (or a full play of the song), as the effects are time-related and can get lost after a long time.
The implemented features refer to the values of Hydra's brightness, contrast and modulation functions, with the lowest value being the rarest.
The way the song is performed changes every time you click on the screen.

Designed for Desktop/Notebook computers on Google Chrome Version 104.0.5112.102 (64 bits)

metadata.name: The Artifact #458
metadata.description:
An archaeological artifact from the future, when many everyday objects are produced by generative algorithms. Some artifacts are in one piece, and others are fragmented. The color palettes are named after the rivers where artifacts in this design have first been discovered.

URL and interactive features:

- Append &r=<number> to the URL to change the image resolution. For example, &r=0.5 will halve the pixel count along both width and height, and &r=2 will double it.

- Append &d=<number> to the URL to change the pixel density. For example, &d=0.3 will generate a very quick, coarse render, and &d=2 will generate very fine stippling.

- Append &p to the URL to reveal detailed parameter settings used for the artwork.

- Append &h to the URL to suppress the notification that rendering is in progress.

- Press 's' in the live view to save the rendered image as a png.

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript. Polygon boundaries are determined via t-SNE, which is implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used. Licensed CC0.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Acrylic #266
metadata.description:
A deep dive into particles is what led me to acrylic. Bright and deep colours with smooth lines while all connected in the journey to the target. 
My main inspiration was the smooth movement of a flock to a endpoint and where a particle should go if not one but multiple points present itself. Make sure you take a look at the live view to see every detail of the piece. 


Generated with code using p5.js
Images are generated at 1280 x 2048px 
(all the way up to 7680 * 12288). 

[Options]:
To save a PNG file, please press 'S'.

[URL variables in live view]:
Change size (up to 6): /&density=6
